1. Find a tree decomposition of the graph.
2. Compute the width of the tree decomposition.
3. The treewidth of the graph is the minimum width over all possible tree decompositions.

A tree decomposition of a graph G is a tree T where each node of T is a subset of vertices of G, called a bag, such that:

1. The union of all bags is equal to the vertex set of G.
2. For each edge (u, v) in G, there is a bag containing both u and v.
3. If a vertex v is in two bags, then it is in every bag on the path between those two bags in T.

